<section class="philosophical-perspectives">
    <h2>Philosophical Perspectives</h2>

    <div class="perspective-cards">
        <div class="perspective-card" data-perspective="material">
            <h3>Material Identity</h3>
            <div class="icon-container">
                <div class="icon material"></div>
            </div>
            <p>
                Focuses on the physical composition of the ship. If all original materials 
                are replaced, can it be considered the same object?
            </p>
            <div class="tooltip">
                "The physical continuity argument suggests that material composition 
                determines identity."
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="perspective-card" data-perspective="form">
            <h3>Form & Function</h3>
            <div class="icon-container">
                <div class="icon form"></div>
            </div>
            <p>
                Considers the ship's purpose and design. If it maintains the same function 
                and form, does the material matter?
            </p>
            <div class="tooltip">
                "Aristotelian philosophy emphasizes form over matter in determining essence."
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="perspective-card" data-perspective="continuity">
            <h3>Temporal Continuity</h3>
            <div class="icon-container">
                <div class="icon temporal"></div>
            </div>
            <p>
                Examines the gradual nature of change. Does continuous transformation 
                preserve identity through time?
            </p>
            <div class="tooltip">
                "The gradual replacement process maintains a continuous thread of identity."
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="discussion-questions">
        <h3>Questions for Reflection</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>If we built a second ship from the original parts, which would be the true Ship of Theseus?</li>
            <li>How does this paradox relate to personal identity through physical change?</li>
            <li>What role does collective memory and social recognition play in object identity?</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="references">
        <h3>Classical References</h3>
        <div class="reference-list">
            <div class="reference">
                <span class="author">Plutarch</span>
                <span class="work">Life of Theseus</span>
                <q>The ship wherein Theseus and the youth of Athens returned...</q>
            </div>
            <div class="reference">
                <span class="author">Thomas Hobbes</span>
                <span class="work">De Corpore</span>
                <q>That ship of Theseus concerning the difference whereof made by continued reparation...</q>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

